<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Trade Deficit Climb Up to 10.2 Bln Dlrs in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. trade deficit surged
to 10.2 billion U.S. dollars in May, the U.S. Commerce Department
reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The 17 percent increase from some 8.7 billion dollars in April
in the monthly deficit is the biggest imbalance in four months,
and was worse than some analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
In May, imports of goods and services increased 1 percent,
pushing them to a record high of 87.47 billion dollars, also
representing growth for a seventh straight month. Meanwhile,
exports fell a slight 0.8 percent to 77.24 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
America's foreign oil bill rose 8 percent to 5.3 billion
dollars as higher volume offset a slight decline in price. The
average price for a barrel of crude oil declined for the fourth
straight month, falling from 17.17 dollars in April to 17 dollars
a barrel in May, the lowest level in 15 months.
</P>
<P>
Imports of foreign cars and auto parts were up 331 million
dollars to 11.7 billion dollars in May despite the fact that auto
shipments from Japan declined by 256 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.S. government's report, the deficit with
China climbed 9.1 percent to 3.8 billion dollars, the worst
showing in seven months, as imports of Chinese toys climbed by 110
million dollars and shipments of shoes and clothing also showed
big increases. It marked the third month that the deficit with
China had surpassed that with Japan.
</P>
<P>
The deficit with Japan had a sharp 25 percent drop to 3.6
billion dollars in May. However, the improvement came after
several months of big increases. So far this year, the deficit
with Japan is running 14 percent higher than the imbalance for the
first five months of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The trade gap widened by a big margin with America's two
members of the North America Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA). The
imbalance with Mexico climbed 22 percent to an all-time high of
1.7 billion dollars. The deficit with Canada more than doubled to
1.7 billion dollars as imports from Canada climbed to 14.5 billion
dollars, the highest figure ever for a single country.
</P>
<P>
Economists attributed the country's foreign trade troubles to a
variety of factors. The U.S. dollar, until recently, has been
strengthening against other key currencies, making foreign goods
cheaper in this market and America exports more expensive
overseas.
</P>
<P>
In addition, key U.S. export markets including Japan and Europe
have been struggling with weak growth, cutting into American
sales, while the U.S. economy has been surging this year, pushing
up demand for both domestic and foreign products.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the U.S. trade deficit in goods and services
is running at an annual rate of 115.4 billion dollars, which is
expected to surpass the imbalance of 111 billion dollars last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
