<HEADLINE> Canada's Consumers, Businesses More Confident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Canadian consumers and businesses
have become more confident in the country's economy and are more
willing to spend, said reports today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Conference Board of Canada, Canadian consumer
confidence reached in the second quarter its highest level in
eight years, and business confidence registered its top reading
since it began its survey in 1977.
</P>
<P>
It was the sixth consecutive increase for the index of consumer
attitudes of the board, an Ottawa-based economic think tank.
</P>
<P>
Almost 60 percent of the consumers surveyed said it was a good
time to make a major purchase.
</P>
<P>
"It's finally reached a point where we feel it's breaking
through a barrier of some kind," Paul Darby, director of the
board's economic services, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The board's consumer index reached 116.2, up from 108 in the
first quarter of the year. At its latest level, the index is
closing in on the readings in the 120s that characterized Canada's
boom years of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Yet, Canadian consumers are still a bit wary about their own
finances. More than half said they expected no change in their
financial condition in the next six months, while 16 percent
expected it to worsen.
</P>
<P>
The after-tax income of Canadians fell 1 percent in real terms
from the first quarter of 1996 to the first quarter of 1997 and
consumers are carrying a heavy debt load, the board noted.
</P>
<P>
In a separate survey, the board found that Canadian businesses
were even more buoyant than consumers.
</P>
<P>
Its index of business confidence rose to a record 165 from
160.1 in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
More than 77 percent of the companies polled said it was good
time to invest in plant and equipment.
</P>
<P>
And 36 percent said they planned to increase capital spending
by more than 10 percent in the next six months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
