<HEADLINE> Northern Irish Peace Talks Discussed in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- British and Irish ministers met
here today to try to maintain the momentum towards substantive
all-party talks on the issue of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
After their three-hour meeting, Britain's Northern Ireland
Secretary Mo Mowlam and Irish Foreign Minister Ray Burke expressed
welcome to a statement by Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams in which he
said the two governments had removed some obstacles to meaningful
negotiations on Northern Ireland's future.
</P>
<P>
The statement was issued jointly by Adams, whose party is the
political wing of the Irish Republican Army (IRA), and John Hume,
leader of the province's largest Catholic party, the Social
Democratic and Labor Party, after talks Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"It is our view that the peace process can be restored and that
with political will on all sides we can move towards a new
political agreement," they said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the statement would help efforts to establish
peace in the province, Northern Ireland Secretary Mowlam told
reporters, "I hope it is a precursor, but I think we will have to
wait and see where we go from that statement."
</P>
<P>
Irish Foreign Minister Burke said, "Obviously I welcome the
statement." "I hope that we will have an early restoration of the
unequivocal IRA cease-fire and I hope it will be sooner rather
than later," he added.
</P>
<P>
The IRA abandoned a 17-month cease-fire in February last year,
resuming its 28-year struggle for a united Ireland. Britain and
Ireland insist it must lay down its arms again if it is to join
all-party talks on the future of the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
