<HEADLINE> Pele Named WHO Ambassador for Leprosy Elimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Former world soccer star Pele of
Brazil was named by the World Health Organization (WHO) as a
"goodwill ambassador" for eliminating of leprosy around the world,
a WHO press release said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 57-year-old Pele, who's real name is Edson Arantes do
Nascimento, is the Minister of Sport of Brazil and was considered
the world greatest striker during 1958 and 1970, scoring a total
of 1281 goals in 1363 matches.
</P>
<P>
WHO sets a target to eliminate this ancient disease by the year
2000, reducing the prevalence of the disease, worldwide, to less
than one case per 10,000 population.
</P>
<P>
There are some 888,340 known cases of leprosy in the world but
WHO estimates that there are 1.15 million.
</P>
<P>
Pele is already involved in leprosy elimination campaigns in
Brazil, the second worst leprosy-hit country with a total of
106,000 cases behind India, which has more than 500,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
