<HEADLINE> Canada's Electronic Banking to Increase Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Banking by Internet, phone and
debit card is expected to soar in Canada over the next three
years, said a report today.
</P>
<P>
Computer banking -- primarily on the Internet -- is expected to
skyrocket by 450 percent in Canada over the three years, according
to Ernst &AMP; Young Canada, a company that did a 17-country study of
banking and financial institutions recently.
</P>
<P>
Banking in cyberspace is just getting going now, but the
Internet "is going to be one of the fastest growing distribution
channels within the next three years," said Ali Hamza, a principal
of the company.
</P>
<P>
The survey also suggests comparable growth in the use of
banking by phone and an 82 percent rise in such things as debit
card transactions by 1999.
</P>
<P>
"From the bank's point of view, technology banking is lower
cost," Hamza was quoted by the Financial Post newspaper as saying.
"From the customer's point of view, it's more convenient."
</P>
<P>
However, bank branching will still remain the No.1 way
Canadians bank, Hamza added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
