<HEADLINE> Kohl Blasts Opposition SPD for Blocking Tax Reform Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 18 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl today
blasted in the upper house of parliament Bundesrat the main
opposition Social Democrats (SPD) for blocking the tax reform
planned by his center-right government.
</P>
<P>
"This is betrayal of the unemployed," said Kohl, who blamed the
country's current tax system for hindering the creation of jobs.
</P>
<P>
Germany's joblessness is now at a near-record 11 percent. The
government's tax reform package would lead to a net 30 billion
mark (16.7 billion US dollar) tax cut.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Kohl accused the SPD, which holds the
majority in Bundesrat, of cold-bloodedly seeking to block a
government tax reform success without caring what price Germans
paid for the tactic.
</P>
<P>
Kohl noted that the SPD intended to see worsened unemployment
so that they could exploit this in the upcoming election in
September 1998. He added that he was willing to negotiate a
compromise tax bill with the opposition and threatened to make the
SPD blockade a key issue in the general election, in which he
plans to seek a fifth four-year term.
</P>
<P>
"I have no doubt, (my) coalition will win the next election,"
said Kohl.
</P>
<P>
Kohl also said that besides tax, pension and healthcare
reforms, European integration and binding together eastern and
western Germany remained the top priorities for his government
prior to the election.
</P>
<P>
The German chancellor today also reiterated his determination
not to allow the membership criteria of the planned single
European currency, the euro, to be watered down, nor the startup
of the euro scheduled for January 1, 1999 to be delayed.
</P>
<P>
Kohl also repeated his pledge that Germany would meet the
budget deficit limit of 3 percent of the gross domestic product as
required to qualify for the euro membership. Germany has failed to
do so over recent years.
</P>
<P>
Kohl predicted Germany's economic growth would be up to 3
percent in 1998, compared to an expected 2.5 percent growth this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
