<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peacekeepers Urged to Be Conversant With UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Chief of Staff of the air force of
Zimbabwe, Henry Muchena today called on forces involved in
peacekeeping operations to be conversant with the UN charter
governing them.
</P>
<P>
Muchena made the remarks after closing a five-day seminar on
military justice and peacekeeping, reported the Zimbabwe News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
"Member states of the United Nations are individually bound by
that charter, and any violation of the law of war by a force of
any member state is the sole responsibility of that country," he
said.
</P>
<P>
As armies are now more challenged by peacekeeping operations,
the military faces a legal problem because each country has its
own rules so it is important to understand and adhere to a common
charter that governs them all, he said.
</P>
<P>
In his address to officers from the army, airforce, police and
the Defense Ministry, Muchena said that adhering to the U.N. charter
is important for Zimbabwe which has been involved in peacekeeping
operations in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was the fifth in a series conducted by a U.S. team
of instructors under the auspices of the Naval Justice School's
detachment of international training. 
</P>
</TEXT>
