<HEADLINE> Annan Proposes to Renew UNIFIL Mandate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today proposed to renew the mandate of the United Nations
Interim Force on Lebanon (UNIFIL) for a further period of six
months.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the deputy permanent representative of
Lebanon to the United Nations described his government's position
on the situation in southern Lebanon in a letter to the UN chief
and conveyed his government's request that the Security Council
extend the mandate of the UNIFIL for a further period of six
month.
</P>
<P>
In his report, Annan said that during the past six months,
hostilities continued between the Israel Force and its local
Lebanese auxiliary, the de facto force, on the one hand, and armed
elements who have proclaimed their resistance to the Israeli
occupation on the other hand. The level of hostilities was higher
than in the previous period.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that although the UNIFIL continued to be prevented
from implementing its mandate, the contribution to stability and
protection it was able to afford the population of the area
remained important.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief, therefore, recommended that the Security Council
extend the mandate of the UNIFIL for another period of six months
until January 31, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
