<DOCNO> XIE19970719.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Opposition Calls for "Full" Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NAIROBI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan opposition leaders today
called for full constitutional reforms instead of minimum changes
they had advocated before, saying the ruling party's concessions
were "insufficient" and "in deception to buy time".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they demanded a neutral independent electoral
commission to guarantee free and fair elections, equal access to
media for all political parties, as well as a ceiling on election
spending and the state funding for political parties.
</P>
<P>
These are the opposition's three essential demands which
"have not even been touched upon in (the ruling party) KANU's
package of reforms," leader of the National Development Party,
Raila Odinga, said at a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
"FORD-Asili will not accept piecemeal concessions from
(Kenyan President Daniel arap) Moi," said the party's National
Chairman Kenneth Matiba earlier today, charging Moi's shift "is
merely another gimmick" with aims to diffuse the pressure for
reforms.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Kenyan African National Union (KANU) on Thursday
recommended the government put forward a bill in parliament for
enactment of a commission to review the constitution and make
proposals.
</P>
<P>
KANU also suggested that the government issue a Statute Law
bill in the current session of the parliament to allow the repeal
or amendment of laws charged as oppressive.
</P>
<P>
These laws include the Public Order Act on public rallies,
the Preservation of Public Security Act which allows detention
without trial, as well as other nine laws.
</P>
<P>
The opposition National Convention Executive Council (NCEC)
vowed on Thursday to push ahead with mass actions in July and
August#,including a nationwide strike on August 8 to paralyze
business and several rallies in major cities around the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, opposition members of parliament gave Moi nine
pre-conditions for expected talks between Moi and the opposition
next week, urging Moi to pulbicly pledge to undertake the reforms
before the forthcoming general elections.
</P>
<P>
From May to July, violence has been escalating when the
opposition repeatedly tried to hold rallies without governmental
permit in a bid to press for constitutional reforms before the
general elections. All the rallies were broken up by the police.
</P>
<P>
Under the current constitution, any candidate, if he wins no
less than 25 percent of votes respectively in five of the eight
provinces of Kenya, he can be qualified as a legal president.
</P>
<P>
The opposition urges to change the clause, demanding the
future president get more than 50 percent of the total votes
nationwide, otherwise form a coalition government with other
parties.
</P>
<P>
The demand has been refused by the 73-year-old Moi,
who has ruled the country for 19 years. 
</P>
