<HEADLINE> SADC Finance Ministers, Bankers Meet over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Finance ministers and
central bankers from the 12 Southern African Development
Community (SADC) countries met in Pretoria, the capital of South
Africa today to discuss regional economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The delegates had examined "details of economic convergence,"
South African Finance Minister Trevor Manuel told a media
briefing after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The ministers called for a draft finance and investment
protocol to be drawn up by April next year, which would
eventually commit member countries to certain economic norms and
standards, Manuel said.
</P>
<P>
Botswana's Vice-President and Finance Minister Festus Mogae
said macro-economic convergence would take the form of a package,
giving consideration to such factors as investment flows,
inflation, foreign exchange control, and incentive packages.
</P>
<P>
Economic cooperation would be deepened through the creation of
regional sub-committees on investment, macro-economic policy,
development finance and customs and excise, said a media statement
released at the briefing.
</P>
<P>
The 12 SADC countries are Angola, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi,
Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa, Swaziland,
Tanzania, Zamiba and Zimbabwe. 
