<HEADLINE> S.leone Talks Resume in Cote d'Ivoire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 18 (Xinhua ) -- West African foreign ministers
began a second day of talks with representatives of Sierra
Leone's military rulers in Abidjan on Friday as part of efforts
to reverse the May 25 coup there and restore President Ahmad
Tejan Kabbah to power.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here today said that the talks in Cote
d'Ivoire's capital Abidjan adjourned Thursday on a hopeful note
with Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi, saying they had made
substantial progress.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, which heads a west African force trying to restore
peace and democracy to both Sierra Leone and neighbouring
Liberia, has spearheaded efforts to return Kabbah to power.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone's neighbours decided in Guinea on June 26 to
pursue dialogue and economic sanctions to try to persuade the
Sierra Leonean military junta to reinstate Kabbah, but they
retained a military option.
</P>
<P>
Cote d'Ivoire, Nigeria, Ghana and Guinea were given the job of
holding talks with the junta and reporting back to Nigeria's
military ruler, Sani Abacha, current Chairman of the Economic
Community of West African States.
</P>
<P>
``We feel we have made substantial progress and that the
atmosphere exists for a substantial breakthrough,'' Ikimi said
after Thursday's talks. He held separate talks with members of
the Sierra Leonean delegation before Friday's session, reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Liberia holds presidential elections on Saturday to end seven
years of civil war and Ikimi and the other foreign ministers
planned to be there.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian soldiers have clashed with Sierra Leonean troops and
their rebel allies on several occasions since Nigerian gunboats
bombarded the capital on June 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
