<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Prosecutor on Trial of Former Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- the trial of the former
government officials and their followers is one of the main
manifestations of the task to ensure the accountability of
governments to the law and the public, an official said today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, the remarks were made
by Ethiopian Chief Prosecutor Girma Wakjira when he spoke to
local journalists here.
</P>
<P>
Girma said, ''this activity is an unprecedented venture in the
history of Ethiopia and a task that must be undertaken to ensure
that the atrocities committed under the previous government will
never be repeated again in the country.''
</P>
<P>
The trial also serve as a forum to draw lessons on legality,
human rights and the democratic process, and a lesson to
government officials as well so that they can no more commit
crimes with immunity, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The chief prosecutor said the recent resolution by the House
of People's Representatives to strip off the parliamentary
immunity of two of its members, suspected of involvement in the
atrocities of the former government, is an important measure to
ensuring accountability and responsibility of government
officials for their actions.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it is a big reward to those of us at the special
prosecutors office, and a clear indication of the government's
commitment to the administration of justice, he added.
</P>
<P>
The trial of former government officials started in December,
1994. Forty-five former government officials were brought into
dock. These defendants are accused of genocide and crimes against
humanity. 
</P>
