<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 30,000 Bosnian Refugees Repatriated From Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 18 (Xinhua) -- More than 30,000 Bosnian refugees
were repatriated from Germany in the first six months of 1997, the
office of the UN High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) said here
today.
</P>
<P>
According to the UN refugee agency, a total of 60,000 Bosnian
refugees have returned home from Germany since the signing the
Dayton peace accords in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
Germany has taken in about 350,000 Bosnian refugees since 1992,
far more than any other European countries.
</P>
<P>
Uneasy with the heavy financial burden of hosting refugees,
estimated at 3 billion U.S. dollars a year, German local
authorities have mounted increasing pressure on the refugees to
return home voluntarily. Otherwise, they could face deportations.
</P>
<P>
But Germany's repatriation plans have met with strong protests
from refugees, especially Bosnian Muslims whose homes lie in what
are now areas controlled by Serbs.
</P>
<P>
The United States has also called on Germany not to repatriate
Bosnian refugees who are unable to return home for fear of ethnic
violence.
</P>
<P>
Declaring that Bonn needs no advice on how to deal with
refugees, German officials stressed that since the fighting has
stopped, Bosnian refugees should return home to participate in the
rebuilding of their country, just as Germans did after World War
II. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
