<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Expected to Return to Somali Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 18 (Xinhua)-- Religious leader Sheikh Ali
Sheikh Mohamud (Sheikh Ali Dhere), arrived here this afternoon
after over two months' stay in Saudi Arabia and pledged to
restore the Islamic sharia law and order in north Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Arriving on a small Cesna plane at the Issaley airstrip, 15 km
north of Mogadishu, the Sheikh was welcomed by hundreds of
cheering people with placards urging the implementation of the
sharia laws.
</P>
<P>
The religious leader was then escorted by about 30 battle
wagons and more than 300 armed militiamen to the main streets of
north Mogadishu. Hundreds of sympathizers of the sharia law
gathered at the playing ground of Karan where the Sheikh made a
speech.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Mohamud said he has returned to his people so as to
restore the rule of the Islamic law in north Mogadishu. He also
promised the people that the Islamic sharia courts will be
revived and the bandits will be dealt with severely.
</P>
<P>
According to Sheikh Mohamud the Islamic sharia law are the
only means that can lead the people to a better living and real
co-existence.
</P>
<P>
The crowd pledged their support to the Sheikh and the
implementation of the sharia law, before dispersing peacefully
with a hope that security matters will be straightened up.
</P>
<P>
The Sheikh also thanked the people and consoled them for the
hard times they've been living during the period when the Islamic
courts had been dormant.
</P>
<P>
The arrival of the Islamic leader came at a time when the
security situation of north Mogadishu is almost out of control.
Killing of innocent people, abduction and widespread banditry
activities in broad day light have been very common in the
streets of north Mogadishu controlled by the faction led by Ali
Mahdi Mohamed.
</P>
<P>
The security of north Mogadishu went out of hand when Ali
Mahdi issued a decree sacking Sheikh Mohamud from the
chairmanship of the Islamic courts in October last year.
</P>
<P>
One-third of the young men are carrying assault rifles with
them in the streets of north Mogadishu nowadays. Every vehicle
is driven with at least two guns for its protection from
freelance looters.
</P>
<P>
Armed confrontations between supporters of Ali Mahdi and
Sheikh Mohamud had claimed several lives before the Sheikh flew
to Saudi Arabia two months ago.
</P>
<P>
However, a mediation by the elders from the Abgal Clan where
both men belong to, had resulted in the renomination of Sheikh
Muhamud to his former post.
</P>
<P>
At the moment,it is not yet clear whether Sheikh Muhamud will
succeed in his new attempts to restore the rule of the sharia
law, but the people of north Mogadishu are fed up with insecurity
in their part of the capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
