<HEADLINE> Tanzania Bans Bikini in Beauty Contests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania government
insists on a ban on bikini in beauty contest in the country, an
official from the Ministry of Education and Culture told Xinhua
today.
</P>
<P>
The official quoted Juma Athuman Kapuya, minister of Education
and Culture as saying recently that his ministry will not
tolerate behaviors which break morality and ethics of the
society.
</P>
<P>
"Our decision to ban the use of bikinis still stands," said
Kapuya, adding, "we are not ready to allow our girls walking half
naked only to satisfy the interests of a few."
</P>
<P>
The minister insisted that cultural values should be upheld in
all beauty contests staged in Tanzania to avoid the influence of
external cultures intended to ruin the nation morally.
</P>
<P>
He said beauty pageants are allowed in so far as they promote
and portray good values of some traditions.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot imitate other cultures now in decay," Kapuya
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Miss Tanzania, the first beauty contest in the country, was
held in the capital city of Dar es Salaam in 1994, which has been
followed by many beauty pageants.
</P>
<P>
However, even now some people are still lack of enthusiasm
about the contests due to the government's insistence on banning
bikinis at the events. 
</P>
</TEXT>
