<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Challenges Ahead for Liberia's New Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- As all is ready for tomorrow's
election in Liberia, the international community has turned its
eyes to the challenges ahead of the incoming democratic
government of the war-ravaged country.
</P>
<P>
The main task, according to observers, would be the
reconstruction of the country, economic recovery, national
reconciliation and re-establishment of security.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, in its 1997 report which reached here today,
stressed the need for greater caution with special attention to
the distortions in the economy brought about by the conflict and
the encouragement of private investment.
</P>
<P>
"Policies to spur the private sector's recovery should
therefore avoid overly aggressive increase in taxation and should
stress the early sequencing of investment-sensitive reforms such
as low inflation, and restraint in revenue collection," it said.
</P>
<P>
However, the report warned that avoiding aggressive revenue
collection does not mean offering overly generous tax incentives
for private foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Such investment could be counter-productive as it would not
only deprive the government of substantial revenue but also slow
the revival of domestic investment, it added.
</P>
<P>
Although the west African peace-keeping force, ECOMOG, has
tightened security for the coming election, it will still be a
tough challenge for the new government to maintain security
following the withdrawal of ECOMOG six months after the
government is installed in early August.
</P>
<P>
The election will put an end to the seven-year civil war in
Liberia, but it does not lead automatically to the end of
insecurity, observers said.
</P>
<P>
Fear of violence or theft might actually increase, giving rise
to more opportunities for criminal activities, the World Bank
report predicted.
</P>
<P>
The bank also called for efforts to strengthen Liberia's local
police force and the need to tighten the enforcement of criminal
laws and other measures to reduce the risk of banditry and
criminal enterprise.
</P>
<P>
With more than 20 tribes in the country, the new government
should also take special consideration of their various interests
so as to achieve national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Contradictions among rival tribes are one of the root causes
of the prolonged turbulence in the country.
</P>
<P>
All the presidential aspirants of Liberia's 13 political
parties have promised hope of education, jobs and equal
opportunity for all during their campaign exercise.
</P>
<P>
Awaiting one of the candidates who is to become the president
after the election however, is how to turn the promise into
reality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
