<HEADLINE> UNESCO Adult Education Meeting Closes in Hamburg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The 5th United Nations Education,
Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) congress on adult
education concluded today in the northern German port city of
Hamburg, which set concrete educational goals for adults in the
next decade.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from 160 countries agreed during the five-day meeting
on a "Declaration on Adult Education" and an "Agenda for the
Future".
</P>
<P>
The Agenda, adopted at the close of the conference, calls for
member countries to spend six percent of their gross domestic
product (GDP) on educational programs.
</P>
<P>
Especially in order to improve the women education in poorer
countries, the document urges UNESCO member countries to create
conditions that theoretically allow everyone to spend an hour a
day learning.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Agenda addresses the educational needs of
minorities and native people as well as senior citizens and the
handicapped.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO member countries pledged to report regularly on the
progress in implementing their educational goals.
</P>
<P>
The conference chairwoman, German parliament speaker Rita
Suessmuth, believed that the results of the conference would "play
a key role in putting the idea of adult education squarely on the
political agenda of countries around the world. "
</P>
<P>
The UNESCO conference on adult education was held every 12
years beginning 1949. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
