<HEADLINE> Bell Canada to Cut 2,200 More Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Bell Canada has announced it plans
to cut 2,200 more jobs this year to deal with tough competition in
Canada's long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
Bell Canada, the country's largest telephone company, has lost
a 33-percent share of the 8 billion Canadian dollars long-distance
market since competition was introduced in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Two-thirds of the 2,200 reductions will be from management
ranks, and the rest from administrative support workers, said
Bell's president John McLennan.
</P>
<P>
"We are facing market and price pressures from competitors who
are intensifying their efforts at a much faster pace than
expected," McLennan was quoted as saying by reports today.
</P>
<P>
Bell is in the third and final year of a massive 1.7 billion
dollar restructuring program, which was intended to reduce its
work force by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
With this latest move, Bell hopes to reduce its work force to
38,100 by the end of December, down from 44,895 at the end of
1996. 
</P>
