<HEADLINE> EU Withdraws Grant for Italian SMEs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)'s
executive body, the European Commission, has decided to withdraw a
grant of 6.5 million ECUs (about 8.5 million U.S. dollars) for
Italy's small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The EU's global grant was approved for the creation and
development of the SMEs in Italy. The decision was taken because
the grant was not put into action, sources said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The agency administering the money, Finanziaria Meridionale
SpA, was reportedly not capable of providing the Ministry of
Treasury with a bank guarantee to cover the risks linked to the
administration of the grant.
</P>
<P>
With this action, the EC wants to show its determination to
protect the financial interests of the EU, says a press release
issued in Brussels Friday.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal of funding is not necessarily linked to fraud or
irregularities but might be also due to technical difficulties or
operating problems which might arise during the implementation of
a project, an EU spokesman explained.  
</P>
