<HEADLINE> U.S. Reaffirms Stand against Hun Sen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Friday
reaffirmed its stand against Cambodia's Co-Prime Minister Hun Sen
on the eve of U.S. special envoy Stephen Solarz takes his Asian
trip on a mission to resolve the Cambodia crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that Mr Hun Sen has illegally and unfairly usurped
the power of the democratically elected authorities, the fact that
he has tried to intimidate Prince (Norodom) Ranariddh from not
returning to Cambodia, the fact that he is trying to install the
Cambodian foreign minister into the position of first prime
minister, all without any recourse to democratic procedures, is
very disturbing to us," State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns
said at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
Solarz, at the request of Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, will fly to Asia on Saturday in an effort to rally
support for the U.S. position from Asian governments. He will hold
talks with leaders of visiting countries, including Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen, who has ousted Ranariddh as the first prime minister
by force early this month, said on Thursday that he accepted
Foreign Minister Ung Huot to take the place of Ranariddh as the
first prime minister.
</P>
<P>
But Burns said Ranariddh is still the first prime minister of
Cambodia, "the Cambodian people put his there."
</P>
<P>
"We're not willing to concede that we should do nothing when
democracy has been flouted so brazenly by Hun Sen in Cambodia," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Ranariddh had conceded in Thailand that his
forces were no match for Hun Sen's and agreed to call of armed
resistance to his rival.
</P>
<P>
And Solarz's mission seemed inclined more th a "post-coup
strategy" than to restoring Cambodia's ruptured coalition
government, observers said.
</P>
<P>
However, Burns said Solarz's mission is more than listening
to the views of the leaders he is going to meet, but "to put
forward a very vigorous point of view by the United States that
the status quo cannot be tolerated." 
</P>
