<HEADLINE> Canada Protests to U.S. Over Salmon Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government today
accused the United States of breaking the Pacific Salmon Treaty
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Ottawa has sent a sternly worded diplomatic note to Washington,
which says Americans are violating international laws and demands
the Alaskan salmon fishery end immediately to preserve
Canadian-bound sockeye stocks.
</P>
<P>
"We are not sending them a letter... We are sending a note to
the government of the United States saying you are now in breach
of an international treaty," Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister
Lloyd Axworthy was quoted as saying today by reports.
</P>
<P>
Alaskan fishermen have caught at least three times the limit of
sockeye permitted under the old Pacific Salmon Treaty, charged
Canadian Fisheries Minister David Anderson.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that Canadian fishermen are taking heavier
losses than the Americans in the ongoing Pacific salmon war.
</P>
<P>
U.S. fishermen of Alaska state are carrying out an
unprecedented interception of Canada-bound fish on the northern
coast, according to Glen Clark, premier of the Canadian province
of British Columbia (B.C.).
</P>
<P>
The Alaskans could catch 10 times their limit of Canadian
sockeye by the end of the month, leaving B.C. fishermen with
reduced catch limits, the premier said.
</P>
<P>
Clark said he was appalled to learn that Alaska is catching an
unprecedented number of Canadian sockeye.
</P>
<P>
Fishermen from the U.S. state have already caught 400,000
Canadian sockeye, despite a limit of 120,000. The number is
expected to reach one million by August.
</P>
<P>
"This clearly escalates the dispute far beyond what many people
thought," Clark was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It is the first time they've been up front about the fact that
this is a full-scale fish war and that they're determined to
violate every conservation principles," he said.
</P>
<P>
The premier believed that it's time for Canada to retaliate.
</P>
<P>
Since the salmon dispute broke out between Canada and the
United States four years ago, both countries have stuck by the
provisions of the Pacific Salmon Treaty, even though they could
not agree on how to renew it.
</P>
<P>
And the sockeye limit in northern waters is part of the treaty
still in place, said an international advisory with Canada's
Fishery Department.
</P>
<P>
"This year, they've obviously gone bananas," he said of Alaskan
fishermen.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the huge Alaskan fishery, Canada will be forced
to reduce the number of sockeye B.C. fishermen could catch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970719.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y. Stocks Pull Back Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 18 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks pulled back
sharply Friday, erasing most of the week's gains, as a
surprisingly higher consumer confidence report scared away some
investors.
