<P>
Bonds stumbled in Friday morning after a University of Michigan
report unexpectedly revealed a sharp improvement in consumer
sentiment during the first half of July. Interest rates edged a
little higher, but remained near their lows for the year.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume was very heavy again at
585.61 million shares. For the week, about 2.96 billion shares
were traded on the NYSE, and some 3.66 billion were traded on the
Nasdaq Stock Market, the biggest tallies ever for both markets.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 16.31 to 915.30, the
NYSE composite index fell 6.99 to 475.97, and the American Stock
Exchange composite index fell 3.75 to 633.59, putting all three
measures into negative territory for the week.
</P>
<P>
The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index, which had gained
nearly 10 percent during a 10-session streak through Wednesday,
fell 20.86 to 1,547.99, but finished the week with a gain of
45.37.  
</P>
</TEXT>
