<HEADLINE> Irish PM Ahern Hails New Truce in Northern Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern
said in Dublin today that the new ceasefire, declared by the Irish
Republican Army (IRA), would provide a fresh opportunity of
building "a durable and balanced settlement" to the 28-year
Northern Ireland conflict.
</P>
<P>
The IRA guerillas, fighting to end British rule in Northern
Ireland, announced this morning "an unequivocal restoration of
ceasefire" from noon on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with Britain's Sky News, Ahern said:
"I welcome the speedy confirmation that the ceasefire has been
unequivocally restored. I know that it's the beginning of another
phase of work for us."
</P>
<P>
Ahern said he understood scepticism among Northern Ireland's
1.5 million people about the sincerity of the IRA truce after the
guerrillas broke a 17-month ceasefire in last February.
</P>
<P>
"I understand those reservations because people who have borne
the brunt of IRA attacks over the years will of course always have
reservations about this. That's totally understandable," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But isn't the absence of violence far better than listening to
news of people being shot in their beds and people being blown
up?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
On the future of the Northern Ireland peace process, the new
Irish Prime Minister said: "The political solution and resolution
of the conflict is still there to work on. But if we can try and
do that with violence not involved then it will be easier." 
</P>
</TEXT>
