<DOCNO> XIE19970719.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Expands Gun Tracing Program to Crack Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said on Saturday he wants to focus on "locking the back door" on
illegal gun sales by expanding a program tracing firearms used in
crime scenes to 10 more cities.
</P>
<P>
"Make no mistake: Gun traffickers are funneling guns to lawless
youth," Clinton said in his weekly radio address.
</P>
<P>
Since Clinton's Youth Crime Gun Interdiction Initiative started
in 17 cities last year, law enforcement agencies have tracked
37,000 crime guns to their sources -- almost twice as many than
the year before, according to Treasury Department statistics.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in seven years, the rate of juvenile crime
actually dropped, by 2.9 percent in 1995, administration figures
showed.
</P>
<P>
But "children are still killing children," Clinton said. He
said it will take an expanded gun-tracing program, the
continuation of background checks on gun buyers and the
cooperation of Congress to stem that.
</P>
<P>
The president also urged law enforcement agencies to continue
doing background checks on prospective gun buyers, despite the
Supreme Court's decision last month to strike down the part of the
Brady Law that mandates such checks.
</P>
<P>
"To keep guns away from crime-committing youth, we must also
continue to perform background checks on gun-buying adults,"
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Background checks protect the "front door of a gun shop," but
it is the Youth Crime Gun Interdiction Initiative that will watch
over the "back door," he said.
</P>
<P>
A Treasury analysis of the interdiction program found that four
out of 10 crime guns recovered by police were from juveniles and
that the most commonly used weapon for people under 24 was a
semiautomatic pistol.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
