<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 1530 GMT, July 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN -- A Jordanian military court here today sentenced to
life imprisonment with hard labor the soldier that killed seven
Israeli school girls at Baqoura in north Jordan Valley in March.
</P>
<P>
Radio Jordan reported the five-man panel and military judges
said 28-year-old Ahmad Mousa Dakamseh was guilty of murder, but
his crime was not pre-meditated.
</P>
<P>
Corporal Dakamseh faced the death penalty during the
three-month-long trial, but the court finally handed down a life
imprisonment verdict because it thought that the soldier was
mentally unstable.
</P>
<P>
He was on charges of pre-meditated murder, but two
psychiatrists last Sunday recommended that the accused not be
convicted of such a crime.
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Cambodia's ousted First Prime Minister Prince
Norodom Ranariddh said today his FUNCINPEC party and three other
parties were forming a movement aimed at finding a non-violent,
diplomatic solution to the country's political crisis.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh was speaking in Bangkok shortly after Hun Sen
rejected efforts by the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) to find a peaceful solution to the latest crisis in
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh, who was ousted by his rival Second Prime Minister
Hun Sen on July 6 after a weekend of fighting between troops loyal
to the two men, said he preferred a non-violent and diplomatic
solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
But he warned his party would organize armed resistance against
Hun Sen if there was no other choice.
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The Irish Republican Army (IRA) has announced a
ceasefire from noon Sunday, Irish television company RTE reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams asked the IRA on Friday to
restore a ceasefire that collapsed in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein is the political wing of the IRA which is an outlawed
guerrilla group fighting to end the British rule of Northern
Ireland. 
</P>
