<HEADLINE> Russian Peacekeepers to Stay in Abkhazia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Russian Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev said here today that the Russian peacekeeping force in
Abkhazia should stay on after July 31 when its mandate expires.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev told reporters, "Russia wants peace in that region,
and certain changes for the better have occurred in the talks on
the settlement of the Georgian-Abkhazian conflict."
</P>
<P>
"I am sure that Russian troops will stay in Abkhazia and Russia
is not spending too much on the peacekeeping mission there," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The Georgian-Abkhazian military conflict broke out in August
1992 when the Autonomous Republic of Abkhazia in western Georgia
declared itself a sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
With mediation from Russia and other countries, Georgia and
Abkhazia have held peace talks on and off since then. The foreign
ministers of both sides are due to hold a further round of talks
in Geneva next week.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze and
the Abkhazian leadership, Russian peacekeeping troops entered
Abkhazia in mid 1994.
</P>
<P>
Abkhazian Prime Minister Sergei Bagapsh told the Interfax news
agency today, "Abkhazia wants the mandate of the Russian
peacekeeping force extended and flatly rejects the idea put
forward by Tbilisi that Russian peacekeepers must be replaced by a
U.N. force."
</P>
<P>
He accused Georgia of trying to keep Russia out of the
negotiating process and draw in the United Nations and
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
He said Abkhazia had accepted a Russian-proposed protocol to
settle the conflict, which Georgia rejected, and would make no
further concessions. So he doubted any progress would be made in
the talks in Geneva on July 23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
