<HEADLINE> Russian Military Reform to be Finalized by Autumn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Russia's military chiefs are
expected to approve ambitious reforms of the country's armed
forces by the end of September, Russian Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev told reporters Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said the long-awaited military reform proposals were now
being finalized and would be sent to President Boris Yeltsin at
the end of September.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev said the proposals would consist of seven parts,
covering reform of the armed forces proper and other military
areas, resources needed to carry out the reforms and the desired
state of the armed forces, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
President Yeltsin, who promised deep-rooted military reforms
last year, on Wednesday issued the first set of decrees to
re-organize the armed forces, including merging different branches
of the military, cutting the number of troops by almost a third to
1.2 million by the end of next year and cutting defense ministry
and general staff administration costs.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev, who replaced sacked defense minister Igor Rodionov in
May, said the reforms would boost the troops' combat capability by
20 percent.
</P>
<P>
With the first 200,000 military personnel due to be discharged
by the end of the year, Sergeyev said Yeltsin would sign a decree
on financial support for the reforms by the end of July.
</P>
<P>
In spite of criticism over the decrees from ousted security
aide Alexander Lebed, Rodionov and Lev Rokhlin, head of the lower
house of parliament's defense committee, Sergeyev said "there are
no avowed enemies of reform in the army."
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that some of Russia's top military were trying
to slow down reform or change the emphasis on reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
