<HEADLINE> Ranariddh Forms Movement to Solve Cambodia's Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's ousted First Prime
Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh said today his FUNCINPEC party
and three other parties were forming a movement aimed at finding a
non-violent, diplomatic solution to the country's political crisis.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh was speaking in Bangkok shortly after Hun Sen
rejected efforts by the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) to find a peaceful solution to the latest crisis in
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh, who was ousted by his rival Second Prime Minister
Hun Sen on July 6 after a weekend of fighting between troops loyal
to the two men, said he preferred a non-violent and diplomatic
solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
But he warned his party would organize armed resistance against
Hun Sen if there was no other choice.
</P>
<P>
He said the new movement, the Union of Cambodian Democrats
(UCD), wants all nations of the world to reject "the illegitimate
government" in Phnom Penh and to condemn the slaughter of innocent
people. The UCD also urged all nations to suspend international
assistance to Hun Sen's government.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh said he would travel to the capitals of the seven
ASEAN members, Japan, Europe, and the United States to explain
what had happened in his country and seek help from the
international community. He will also ask the United Nations to
help solve the crisis. 
