<HEADLINE> Iraq Urges Iran to Release Iraqi POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 17 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi Foreign Ministry
spokesman today urged Iran to release all the Iraqi POWS held in
Iran during the 1980-88 Iraqi-Iranian war, according to the
official Iraqi News Agency (INA).
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued to the INA, the spoksman also called on
Iran to resume meetings to settle all the issues related to POWs
and those missing in action during the eight-year war.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Iran is still holding several thousands of
 Iraqi POWs, while the Iraqi authorities has released all the
Iranian POWs in 1990 and repatriated them to Iran under the
supervision of the International Committee of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is now holding only 64 Iranians who are not POWs because
they unofficially infiltrated into Iraq in March 1991 to commit
acts of killing, plunder, sabotage and destruction, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also criticized Iran for not respecting the
Third Geneva Convention, which provides that once the hostilities
between two countries end, all POWs must be released and
repatriated without any delay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
