<HEADLINE> 33 Kurdish Rebels Killed in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-three rebels of the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) were killed by security forces in
eastern and southeastern Turkey over the past week, according to
an official statement issued today.
</P>
<P>
Four Turkish government troops and three village guards were
also killed in clashes with PKK, said the statement by the office
of the Emergency Regional Rule.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen rebels were killed in the military operation in the
towns of Yuksekova and Semdinli in Hakkari province linking
Iran. Other PKK militants were killed in provinces of Sirnak,
Tunceli, Van, Batman and Bingol.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said five PKK members were captured and
seven others surrendered to the government troops in the region.
</P>
<P>
Newly-appointed Interior Minister Murat Baseskioglu said today
that the PKK is under control in the region.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News has reported that since the
implementation of Emergency Rule in eastern and southeastern
Turkey 10 years ago, 18,000 PKK rebels, 4,209 security forces
members and 4,245 civilians have been killed in armed clashes and
raids.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a separatist war in eastern adn
southeastern Turkey since August 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
