<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Raise Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait Oil Company (KOC), the
oil production arm of the state-owned Kuwait Petroleum
Corporation conglomerate, is planning to raise its production
capacity to 3.5 million barrels per day (bpd) by the year 2005
from the current 2.4 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by KOC board Chairman and Managing Director
Khaled Yousef al-Flaiji in his interview with official Kuwait News
Agency today.
</P>
<P>
He said that his company stands ready to develop all oilfields
as part of this future strategy although the ambitious plan
would request increase of the technical and administrative
burdens on the KOC.
</P>
<P>
Al-Flaiji said the plan covers all production areas, including
the northern oilfields near Iraqi border where a number of rigs
are at work in the four main oilfields of Al-Abdeli,
Al-Roudatain, Al-Ritqa and Al-Sabriyah.
</P>
<P>
He said production from the northern fields has been steadily
increasing, adding that the KOC also plans to boost Kuwaiti
largest Burgan oilfield's production as part of its efforts to
raise the country's overall output.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait at present has a sustainable production capacity of
2.4 million bpd and actually produces 2 million bpd of oil in
line with a quota set by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
