<HEADLINE> Pakistan Continues Shuttle Diplomacy in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 19 (Xinhua) -- A senior Pakistani diplomat will
leave for Kabul on Monday to carry forward his shuttle diplomacy
for peace in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"This is an evolving process and we are endeavoring to move
forward in peace efforts," Iftikhar Murshed, Additional Foreign
Secretary, told the media here today.
</P>
<P>
Murshed's visit to Kabul takes place a few days after Iranian
Deputy Foreign Minister Allaudin Broujerdi's visit to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Tehran and Islamabad agreed to use their
influence to persuade the Afghan Islamic Taliban militia and the
rival northern alliance to sit together and find a peaceful
solution to the Afghan conflict.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Murshed held talks with the leadership of the
northern alliance in Mazar-e-Sharif during which all of them
expressed willingness to enter into political dialogue aimed at
bringing peace to Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The northern alliance, based in Mazar-e-Sharif, has forwarded
the idea of setting up a joint political commission for a
broad-based government in Afghanistan while the Taliban called for
unconditional release of their senior officials including foreign
minister Mulla Muhammad Ghous as a confidence-building measure for
talks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
