<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia's Hun Sen Dismisses ASEAN Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's Second Prime
Minister Hun Sen has rejected outside mediation efforts by the
Association of South East Asian Nations (ASEAN), Indonesian
Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said today.
</P>
<P>
Alatas, who arrived in Phnom Penh today with Thai Foreign
Minister Prachuab Chaiyasarn and Domingo Siazon of the
Philippines, said ASEAN would now stop trying to promote dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"We were given quite a clear indication that...Hun Sen believes
that ASEAN at this stage should not contribute to any solution,
that they themselves would find a solution," Alatas told reporters
after talks with Hun Sen. "Clearly as of this moment our efforts
will stop," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen's spokesman Svay Sitha said, "We think that at present
the royal government does not need ASEAN to take part in helping
solve the issue."
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from the seven-nation ASEAN last week
appointed Alatas as a special envoy to try and help resolve the
political crisis in Cambodia which saw Hun Sen oust his rival
First Prime Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh on July 6 after a
weekend of fighting between troops loyal to the two men.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN also postponed Cambodia's imminent entry into the
grouping.
</P>
<P>
The three ASEAN envoys met King Norodom Sihanouk in Beijing on
Thursday and ousted First Prime Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh,
King Sihanouk's son, in Bangkok on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Alatas said both Sihanouk and Ranariddh were in favor of
ASEAN's help in finding a solution to Cambodia latest political
problems.
</P>
<P>
He denied ASEAN was interfering in Cambodia's affairs because
it was consulting all parties to the conflict. He said he hoped
elections scheduled for next May would go ahead. Hun Sen has said
he wants the poll date to be kept.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen was due to hold a news conference on Saturday afternoon
but later canceled it. His troops took complete control of the
capital on July 6 and fighting has been taking place in northern
Cambodia between Hun Sen's forces and those loyal to Ranariddh's
royalist FUNCINPEC party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
