<HEADLINE> Iranian President: Iran's Cultural Values </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani has said that the cultural values in his country are
different from western ones.
</P>
<P>
"Our system, with its peculiarities...is an unfamiliar system
for the world, especially the West. Naturally our values collide
with theirs," Rafsanjani said in an interview with the
Persian-language daily Jomhuri Islami, which was published today.
</P>
<P>
"We have had and will continue to have these challenges (from
the West)," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the strained relations between Iran and Germany, Rafsanjani
said that the German government came under pressures from the
U.S. and Israel.
</P>
<P>
"I believe U.S.-Israeli pressures on German media and through
the media on the German government were the main thing that caused
this issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
"What the Germans did was a suicide, that is they were forced
to commit a suicide. It was not wise of the German government
to lose a century of friendship with Iran based on a baseless
allegation," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Berlin court declared in April this year a verdict on the
alleged involvement of Iranian leaders in the murder of four
Kurdish dissidents in the Berlin Mykonos restaurant in 1992.
</P>
<P>
It aroused a large-scale anti-German protest in most parts
of Iran.
</P>
<P>
On Iran's relations with other countries, Rafsanjani said that
Iran was determined more than ever to foster ties with the Third
World countries, especially Africa.
</P>
<P>
He accused the U.S. of putting pressure on African countries to
prevent them from cooperating with Iran.
</P>
<P>
"Now there are plenty of African countries who want to work
with us. But there are serious pressures on Africans not to get
close to us," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
