<DOCNO> XIE19970719.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Passes On Gas Contract Draft To Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian government has
sent the Israel Electric Corporation (IEC) a draft agreement to
pipe natural gas to Israel, reported bi-weekly Israel Business
Today.
</P>
<P>
IEC has however delayed its response pending an Israeli
government decision on the matter, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"The government has placed us in an awkward position," said an
unnamed spokesperson for IEC management. "While we were
instructed, together with other potential buyers of gas, to
commence negotiations with Egypt, we are being prevented from
conducting meaningful and official talks with Egypt," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesperson said that, in the absence of an official
Israeli government decision on the future structure of the natural
gas sector in Israel, not progress can be made with the current
project.
</P>
<P>
To date, no official decision has been forthcoming regarding
the source of Israel's natural gas requirements -- Egypt or
Russia.
</P>
<P>
A delegation from Russian natural gas giant, Gazprom, visited
Israel earlier this month to discuss the possibility of supplying
natural gas to Israel.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Moscow in March, Prime Minister Binjamin
Netanyahu said that Israel may spend billions of dollars to buy
Russian oil and gas in return for Russia's suspension of nuclear
cooperation with Iran, a country regarded by Israel as a major
potential threat to its security.
</P>
<P>
National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon made a follow-up
visit to Moscow last month.
</P>
<P>
Industry observers believe that the duel will eventually be
decided in favor of Egypt, in view of the shorter piping distance
involved and the ensuing cheaper cost of transporting the gas from
Egypt to Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
