<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Official Denies Israeli Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 19 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian police
officer has categorically denied Israeli allegations that three
Palestinian policemen had been involved in terrorist attacks
against Jewish settlers.
</P>
<P>
Jihad Masini, assistant commander of the Palestinian police in
West Bank, told reporters Friday that the three policemen arrested
by the Israeli security forces on Monday night near Nablus, West
Bank, had been on an official mission for the Palestinian Criminal
Investigation Department, according to a report of JMCC, a
Palestinian press service based in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Masini brushed off Israeli charges, saying that the Israelis
were merely trying to stop the Palestinian police officers from
pursuing Palestinians who collaborated with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat said on Friday night that the
Israeli charges were part of a comprehensive campaign against the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Arafat was in Ramallah, West Bank, chairing a leadership
meeting to discuss the latest developments pertaining to the peace
process. He reportedly briefed the participants on the outcome of
his recent visits to Austria and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leadership, which is composed of cabinet
ministers, PLO Executive Committee members, speaker of the
legislative Palestinian Council and president of the Palestinian
Natiolnal Council, also discussed recent Israeli-Palestinian talks
on the outstanding issues including the building of a Gaza airport
and seaport, and "safe passage" between the Gaza Strip and West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian negotiator Nabil Sha'ath, who held the talks with
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, was assigned by the
leadership to initiate fresh international efforts on the peace
process. He flew to Cairo, Egypt today and then to Paris, France
and Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
On the Israeli charges, Sha'ath told reporters on Friday night
that the PNA had received video tape confessions of one of the
three Palestinian policemen and was investigating the event very
seriously.
</P>
<P>
Sha'ath added that the PNA demanded that the three officers
be handed over to it by the Israeli authorities.
</P>
<P>
According to the state-run Israel Radio, a senior Israeli
intelligence official had claimed that the Israeli intelligence
had evidence proving that a senior Palestinian police commander
had ordered a squad under his command to ambush an Israeli car in
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The unnamed official said Israel had the
electronically-intercepted orders handed down from the Gaza police
chief, Brig.-Gen. Hazi Jabali, to Jihad Masini.
</P>
<P>
Israel also charged that the three policemen had been
planning an attack on Jewish settlers at Har Bracha near Nablus.
</P>
<P>
The Israel Defense Forces requested the PNA to arrest Masini,
but the Palestinian side has not responded yet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
