<HEADLINE> Young Volunteers Help Make China's Cities Cleaner And Neater </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of students and
other young people in major Chinese cities today helped clean up
the environment and urged their fellow citizens to keep their
cities clean and beautiful.
</P>
<P>
The young volunteers were in the vanguard of a national drive
to promote more civilized behavior by urban residents.
</P>
<P>
In the nation's capital, more than 10,000 volunteers went to
clean up streets and other areas, remove illegal posters, help
maintain order, and distribute pamphlets on civilized behavior.
</P>
<P>
Students from Beijing University went to six construction sites
to help young workers there from outside Beijing understand the
code of proper behavior and the city's laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, in east China, school children and university
students also helped clean up residential areas and the area set
aside for the Eighth National Games.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 young volunteers in the city of Tianjin gave
water and other items to travelers at the Tianjin Railway Station
and on public buses, and helped clean up the bus and train station.
</P>
<P>
In Harbin, northeast China, young volunteers helped traffic
police maintain order at 48 intersections, and picked up waste at
the side of the airport road.  
</P>
</TEXT>
