<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amir: Qatar to Hold Scheduled Economic Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Qatari Amir Sheikh Hamad Bien
Khalifa al Thani has said that his country would go ahead with
hosting the controversial fourth Middle East and North Africa
economic summit in November.
</P>
<P>
The amir made the remark in an interview carried by today's Al
Rai al-Aam, an Arabic daily in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari monarch told the paper that "we firmly stand by our
commitment to host the economic summit in Doha," despite Syrian
threats to boycott the summit.
</P>
<P>
On Syria's reported rejection of the summit and its call for a
pan-Arab boycott, Sheikh Hamad said that "we fully understand
their position and respect it."
</P>
<P>
Egypt was also reported to have demanded Doha to postpone the
summit, and it would submit the proposal to Arab League (AL)
foreign ministers who are due to meet in the Egyptian capital of
Cairo in September.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jordan and Lebanon also reportedly made clear their
indifference in attending the conference.
</P>
<P>
Among Qatar's allies in the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC),
Saudi Arabia, also a regional power broker and a key U.S. ally,
was the first to announce it would not attend the summit and urged
Qatar to cancel or postpone it.
</P>
<P>
The United Arab Emirates (UAE) said on July 5 that it would
boycott the meeting if no breakthrough in the Middle East peace
talks was made.
</P>
<P>
GCC, a regional political, economic and military group,
consists of the UAE, Saudi Arabia, Qatar, Bahrain, Oman and
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Washington had earlier suggested that Qatar split the summit
events among several venues in the Gulf, allowing participants to
visit several of the six GCC states, diplomats here said.
</P>
<P>
But with Saudi Arabia and UAE publicly expressing their boycott
of the meeting, others are expected to follow suit unless they see
a change in Israeli policies, observers here said.
</P>
<P>
However, Sheikh Hamad pointed out that his government has not
been officially notified by any government of their intentions
to boycott the summit, "except what we see in the press."
</P>
<P>
Qatar has stressed only an AL boycott can stop the summit it
has planned to host with Israel's participation over the protests
of several Arab states.
</P>
<P>
The amir also said he discussed in depth the "dangerous"
situation in the Middle East during his recent talks in
Washington with President Bill Clinton, blaming Netanyahu's
anti-Arab policies for the deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
The previous three Middle East and North Africa economic
conferences were held respectively in Casablanca of Morocco in
1994, Amman of Jordan in 1995 and Cairo of Egypt in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
