<HEADLINE> 7 Rwandan Genocide Suspects Arrested in Nairobi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan police has rounded up
seven Rwandese suspects and handed them over to the United
Nations International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda based in
Arusha, northern Tanzania, Kenya Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The suspects including former Rwandan Premier Jean Kambanda
and former senior military commander Gratien Kabiligi were being
moved to tribunal headquarters, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Also arrested on Friday were Pauline Nyiramasuhuko and her son
Arsene Shalom Ntahobali who is suspected to have prepared
programs on Radio Rwanda containing anti-Tutsi statements.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued yesterday, the tribunal said those
arrested were dignitaries in the former Rwandan regime and are
believed to have contributed immensely to the civil strife in
1994.
</P>
<P>
The arrests, the first action in which the Kenyan government
has actively participated, came just two days after a visit by
Rwandese Vice-President Paul Kagame to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The visit by the Rwandese leader was believed to patch up
relations between Rwanda and Kenya, which had been strained since
the end of 1994 and culminated in the severance of diplomatic
relations last year.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. tribunal was set up in November 1994 to bring to
justice leaders of the genocide of an estimated 500,000 people in
Rwanda in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Before the Friday seizure of suspects in Kenya, a total of 21
people had been indicted by the tribunal while 12 suspects were
put into detention. detention in Arusha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
