<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Soldier Gets Life Imprisonment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 19 (Xinhua) -- A Jordanian military court here
today sentenced to life imprisonment with hard labor the soldier
that killed seven Israeli school girls at Baqoura in north Jordan
Valley in March.
</P>
<P>
Radio Jordan reported the five-man panel and military judges
said 28-year-old Ahmad Mousa Dakamseh was guilty of murder, but
his crime was not pre-meditated.
</P>
<P>
Corporal Dakamseh faced the death penalty during the
three-month-long trial, but the court finally handed down a life
imprisonment verdict because it thought that the soldier was
mentally unstable.
</P>
<P>
He was on charges of pre-meditated murder, but two
psychiatrists last Sunday recommended that the accused not be
convicted of such a crime.
</P>
<P>
An assailant who suffers from an antisocial mental disorder is
globally considered as guilty of lesser charges, they were quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
On March 13, when Dakamseh was praying on his duty, a group of
Israeli girls on a tourist bus saw him and laughed at him, reports
said. The soldier became angry, grabbed a gun from one of his
colleagues and shot at the girls.
</P>
<P>
Seven Israeli school girls were killed and four others wounded,
including a teacher.
</P>
<P>
The same day, Jordanian King Hussein cut off his overseas visit
and went back to Jordan to look into the issue. The next day, the
King went to Israel, visited the families of the victims and paid
condolences to the family members.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
