<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Disagrees With UK, U.S. Over Abacha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Barely a week after Britain and the
United States said they would not accept Nigeria's Head of State
Sani Abacha transforming into President Abacha, France has
taken a different stand.
</P>
<P>
French Ambassador to Nigeria, Phillipe Petier, said Friday the
participation of General Abacha in the country's transition program
and possibility of his becoming civilian president in next year's
election is left to Nigerians alone to decide.
</P>
<P>
No country had the right to oppose the decision of Nigerians on the
matter, the envoy said at a cocktail party to mark the 208th
anniversary of the modern French nationhood in Port Harcourt,
southeastern Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Both campaigns for Abacha as president and criticism of the alleged
move have been increasing in Nigeria recently. Abacha himself had in
an interview with Washington Times said that his decision to contest the
election would be made by his "contituency".
</P>
<P>
Based on the fact that the process of establishing political
parties in Nigeria had been "so one-sided as to guarantee that there
wouldn't be any serious candidate," Britain said it would not accept
General Abacha as president.
</P>
<P>
The United States reportedly shared the same view.
</P>
<P>
But Petier stressed that one country or continent had the right to
oppose the decision of Nigerians on the matter, and said that France
would not pre-empt Nigeria on the issue.
</P>
<P>
He also restated the opposition of France to sanctions as a means
of persuasion, saying "no one can dictate to France neither will
France do the same to any country."
</P>
<P>
He ruled out the possibility of sanctions by the European Union
affecting the participation of Nigeria's national soccer team in the
1998 World Cup coming in France.
</P>
<P>
France would at the appropriate time issue the necessary clearance
to Nigerian players and officials to the world cup, he added.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has come under sanctions by some Western countries,
including Britain, U.S. and Canada, since its Commonwealth membership
was suspended following the execution of nine minority activists in
November 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
