<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Rules Out Retaking Palestinian Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Israel has ruled out retaking
Palestinian cities as an option to deal with Palestinian violence
after conducting simulated military exercises, Israeli state
television reported.
</P>
<P>
The simulation of retaking Palestinian cities showed this
option would only worsen the Israeli-Palestinian conflict and lead
to scores of deaths and hundreds of wounded, according to Channel
I's evening newscast Friday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu last week alluded
Israel might retake Palestinian cities as it grew tougher to
renewed violence to "make them pay a heavy price."
</P>
<P>
However, the report said, both the Israeli government and army
concluded after the simulated military games that although its
troops were capable of completing the mission, the retaking of
Palestinian cities would not be an option.
</P>
<P>
The simulation was carried out by the army a month ago in the
presence of top generals and senior officials from the Israeli
Defense Ministry, Prime Minister's office and Knesset (Parliament)
Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1993 Israeli-Palestinian agreement on the
Palestinian self-rule in Gaza and the West Bank city Jericho and
the 1995 agreement on expansion of Palestinian self-rule to the
rest of West Bank, Israel had withdrawn its troops from Gaza,
Jericho, Bethlehem, Jenin, Kalkilya, Nablus, Ramallah and Tulkarm
by the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, Israel and the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) signed an agreement on Israel's troop redeployment
in the last Israeli-occupied city Hebron following a long delay
and hard negotiations. Israeli troops redeployed from 80 percent
of Hebron, but has maintained control over the rest 20 percent
where about 450 Jewish settlers live.
</P>
<P>
The simulated games were conducted at a time when violent
clashes between Palestinian protesters and Israeli troops flared
in the flashpoint Hebron.
</P>
<P>
In the past months, hundreds of Palestinians were injured in
clashes in Hebron and Gaza Strip, mainly by rubber bullets and
tear gas fired by Israeli soldiers to the stone- and
firebomb-throwers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
