<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 08:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicosia Rejects Proposal for Bicommunal Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government has
rejected a proposal by Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash to
set up special bicommunal police units to work with the
U.N. peacekeeping force in the buffer zone of the island state.
</P>
<P>
The government has also called on Denktash and Turkey to
abandon their attempts to seek recognition of the breakaway state
of the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus, set up in 1983 by the
Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
This was made clear in a government statement issued today in
response to Denktash's statement Thursday upon his return from New
York about the establishment of a joint police force to monitor
the 180-kilometer-long buffer zone between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The security of the buffer zone is maintained by the U.N. peace
keeping force in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Manolis Christofides told reporters that
efforts to solve the Cyprus problem will "move on better if
Denktash gives up his policy to seek through everything
recognition of his self-styled regime," which has only gained
recognition by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Security Council resolution 541 adopted in 1984 considers
the unilateral declaration of independence by the Turkish Cypriots
as "legally invalid" and calls on all states not to recognize
any Cypriot state other than the Republic of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"We have before us a specific course of action, defined by the
two High Level Agreements signed by the two communities on the
island, which provide for a federal republic of Cyprus,"
Christofides stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The Greek Cypriot side will adhere to this course of action,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Denktash's proposal came only a few days before the 23rd
anniversary of Turkey's troops landing on the island following a
Greek Cypriot coup seeking union with Greece. The island has been
divided ever since.
</P>
<P>
To mark the occasion, six Turkish navy vessels have arrived at
the Turkish-controlled northern port of Kyrenia.
</P>
<P>
Christofides said the Cypriot government will make
representations to the U.N. about the Turkish warships' illegal
entry into the territory of the republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
