<HEADLINE> Heart Disease Threatens S. African Blacks: Say </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Heart disease is threatening
health of South Africans, especially the blacks, local medical workers
have warned.
</P>
<P>
There will be a surge in coronary heart disease among blacks in 10
to 15 years unless active steps are taken right now, Derick Raal, head
of the lipid clinic at the Johannesburg Hospital, said in Cape Town
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
"Changes in diet, increase in cigarette smoking, increase in
alcohol consumption and reduction of physical activity are causing an
increase in the number of coronary event -- heart attacks -- in black
patients," Raal said.
</P>
<P>
He said figures from the Johannesburg-based Baragwanath Hospital
showed while there only two heart attacks in black patients per year
10 years ago, the figure had now grown to 200 a year.
</P>
<P>
Raal said like the United States where the incidence of heart
attacks in black patients peaked in the last year or two, South
African blacks have just reached the stage where hypertension and
diabetes, major causes for heart attack, is peaking.
</P>
<P>
According to heart disease experts, heart disease patients usually
have the history of hypertension, diabetes and high blood cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
Within the next few years, with the increase in cholesterol level,
the present rate of 18 people per 100,000 dying from heart attacks is
expected to increase 250 per 100,000 as in the U.S., Raal said.
</P>
<P>
"The answer is not drug therapy for everyone, which could be
horrifically expensive, but education and increasing awareness of
cholesterol as the major underlying factor in the development coronary
artery disease," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
