<HEADLINE> Rafsanjani Attacks Turkey's Anti-Islam Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Iran's President Hashemi
Rafsanjani today attacked Turkey's army generals and the West for
conspiring the oust of former Turkish prime minister Necmettin
Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
According to today's Persian daily Jomhuri Islami, Rafsanjani
said "Erbakan and Refah (Welfare) Party were in power for a year.
But you saw how the bullies of the world did. They forced him out
of power in this manner."
</P>
<P>
The pro-Islamist Erbakan was pressured to step down as prime
minister last month amid growing demand for secularism and threat
from the military to stage a coup to dismantle the government
charged with inching the country toward Islamism.
</P>
<P>
The new government led by Mesut Yilmaz, who vowed to stick to
secularism, has won the vote of confidence in the Turkish
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the confidence vote, Iran had expressed doubt over
Yilmaz's odds of securing the parliament support. Ties between
Tehran and Ankara were strained last March when the two countries
recalled their ambassadors and scaled down political
representation to the level of charge d'affaires.
</P>
<P>
It all began in February when Iranian Ambassador to Ankara
Mohammad Reza Baqeri called on Turkish people to follow Iran's
lead and establish an Islamic country.
</P>
<P>
In a political commentary today, Jomhuri Islami accused
Turkey's new prime minister and the secularist generals of staging
a coup against Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
"Mesut Yilmaz and his backers in the military and political
camps staged a coup against Erbakan's Islamic government and
forced him out of Turkey's political scene," the daily wrote.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the recent rejection of Turkey's application for
membership in the European Union (EU), the commentary said EU
still did not consider secularist Turkey worthy of membership.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the secularists attempts to ingratiate themselves (by
forcing Erbakan out of power), the EU thinks Turkey does not
deserve to become a member," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
