<HEADLINE> Rafsanjani: Iran Serious in Military Buildup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Hashemi
Rafsanjani indicated here today that Tehran is seriously involved
in military build-up nine years after its the war with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Reconstruction of the armed forces is very costly. We are
doing all that," Rafsanjani said in an interview carried by
today's edition of the Persian language daily Jomhuri Islami.
</P>
<P>
"We spent all of our strategically-defensive resources in the
(1980-1988) war (with Iraq). Now we have to reach a sure
position. If, God forbid, there is another event (war), we should
be ready," he said.
</P>
<P>
He elaborated by adding "Especially since our peace with Iraq
has not been finalized and we still have POWs. The Iraqis have yet
to pay our reparations. Some of our lands are still filled with
explosives and mines."
</P>
<P>
However, Tehran's major concerns are believed to be the threat
to its national security and potential military attacks by the
United States and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The 64-year-old president warned early this year that Iran
will powerfully respond to any possible military measures by the
U.S., which he said has harbored deep malice toward Iran
following the victory of its Islamic Revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
To confront potential military attack by the U.S., Iranian
decision-makers have raised military budget by about 40 percent in
the new fiscal year starting March 21, 1997.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Iran has allocated 25 billion rials (8.3
million U.S. dollars) on projects to confront U.S. conspiracies
against the country.
</P>
<P>
During the interview, the president blamed the U.S. and
Britain for existing problems in relations between Iran and other
Arab countries in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
"The main problem in the region has to do with the influence of
the U.S. and Britain. It is not in their interests that Iran would
have friendly ties with the neighboring Muslim countries," he
added.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the Arab-Israeli conflict, Rafsanjani said "If
we and the Arabs had coordinated our actions, the politics of the
Middle East and Palestine would have been different."
</P>
<P>
When talking of Iran's ties with Saudi Arabia, Iran's arch
rival in the Gulf and in the Islamic world, Rafsanjani maintained
that Tehran and Riyadh were more inclined to have a rapprochement
at a time of stalked Arab-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"They (Saudi King Fahd ibn Abdul-Aziz and Crown Prince Abdullah
ibn Abdul-Aziz) are naturally more inclined to talk with Iran in
the new conditions in the Middle East," he said.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Deputy Finance Minister Abdul-Aziz Bin Abdullah
al-Khoweiter, envoy of the Saudi king, was here on July 1 to
convey to Rafsanjani messages from the Saudi monarch and the crown
prince.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani told the daily that the messages stressed that Saudi
leaders were interested in helping make a success the eighth
summit of Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) to be
held in Tehran in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
