<HEADLINE> ASEAN FMs Hold Talks With Hun Sen on Cambodia Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The envoys from the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) arrived here and held talks
today with Cambodian Second Prime Minister Hun Sen on the latest
situation in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Svay Sitha, the spokesman for Cambodian prime
ministers, said the three-hour talks were held "in a friendly
atmosphere and with mutual understanding".
</P>
<P>
Cambodian Foreign Minister Ung Huot, who has been nominated for
First Prime Minister to replace Prince Norodom Ranariddh, also
attended the talks.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN foreign ministers, Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas, Prachuab Chaiyasarn of Thailand and Domingo Siazon of the
Philippines, said that their mission here is to exchange views
with the Cambodian government on the latest developments of the
country's situation.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers also wanted to seek options for ASEAN to
help settle the current issue in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
However, Hun Sen said during the talks that the current problem
in Cambodia is neither political nor military, but purely a legal
one.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed international efforts to end the crisis, including
help from ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
"We can solve our own problems within the framework of the
constitution and laws," Hun Sen said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the prime minister suggested ASEAN reconsider its
decision to postpone admission of Cambodia to the group, saying
"the decision was hastily made".
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN foreign ministers said at the end of the meeting that
the talks with Hun Sen enabled them to obtain more profound
understanding of the Cambodian issue.
</P>
<P>
They pledged to make a report to all ASEAN heads and foreign
ministers on Cambodia's position on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Before meeting with Hun Sen, the ASEAN envoys had also held
talks with Cambodian King Norodom Sihanouk in Beijing and the
ousted First Prime Minister Ranariddh in Thailand. 
</P>
