<HEADLINE> Egypt: Peace March Should Not Stop Despite Hurdles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has maintained that the
Arab-Israeli negotiating process should not stop despite
hindrances and Israel's "illegal" measures that run counter to
previously-signed peace deals.
</P>
<P>
This stand was highlighted by Egypt's Ambassador to Tel Aviv
Mohammed Bassiouni in an interview with the Cairo-based Voice of
Arabs radio.
</P>
<P>
The report today quoted him as saying "The 1979
Egyptian-Israeli peace accord was not aimed at achieving
unilateral peace in the Middle East, but rather realizing a
comprehensive settlement in the whole region."
</P>
<P>
Bassiouni pointed out the ongoing Egyptian diplomatic effort is
designed to eliminate reasons behind the current stalemated peace
process.
</P>
<P>
He cited as obstacles to peace talks the Israeli settlement
policy in general and the construction of the Har Homa settlement
in East Jerusalem in particular.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace march slid into a crisis with
violence renewing in West Bank and Gaza, after Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu gave orders in March to build
thousands of Jewish homes at a East Jerusalem hillside.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians hold that the peace crisis was a result of
Israel's settlement building while Israel repeatedly charged that
Palestinian violence was the main obstacle to progress in
peace-making.
</P>
<P>
In the telephone interview with the Arabic-language radio
service, Bassiouni spoke of Cairo's diplomatic campaign to rebuild
Palestinian-Israeli confidence, and its preparations for resuming
peace talks in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian ambassador met Thursday with the top Israeli
diplomat David Levy, in a fresh effort to break the four-month-old
Mideast peace deadlock.
</P>
<P>
He also hosted a meeting between Palestinian chief negotiator
Nabil Shaath and Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai to
narrow their difference concerning the building of an airport in
Gaza to serve the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Egypt stepped in as a main mediator for peace between Israel
and Palestinians after the U.S., sponsor of the Mideast peace
talks, apparently failed to bring the process back on track.
</P>
</TEXT>
