<HEADLINE> Bad Loans Heightens Financial Crisis in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 19 (Xinhua) -- South Korean financial market are
concerned over the large amount of bad loans arising from the
chain of corporate bankruptcies this year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 22 trillion won (890 won: 1 USD) in bad credits has
been extended so far this year to bankrupt conglomerates including
Hanbo and Sammi as well as Kia corporations which are currently
under the shelter of the bankruptcy provention pact.
</P>
<P>
The amount of credits come not only from banks, but also merchant
banks and insurance firms.
</P>
<P>
"The financial market are bombarded by bad loans and the
financial system is on the brink of being brought to a halt,
causing a bad cycle of liquidty crunches and corporate failures,
said a market watcher.
</P>
<P>
He gave a cautious prediction that such a financial crisis will
have a negative effect on the economy, dampening hopes of recovery.
</P>
<P>
The virtual bankruptcy of the country's eighth largest
conglomerate Kia Group is raising doubts about the credit
worthiness of South Korean companies and financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Among financial firms, merchant banks emerged as the largest
victims in the wake of Kia's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
As the 18 Kia subsidiaries came under the shelter of the
bankruptcy protection agreement, merchant banks found they could
not collect on loans extended to them.
</P>
<P>
Some merchant banks even did not expect commercial banks to
apply the bankruptcy prevention pact to Kia.
</P>
<P>
At the end of may, 30 merchant banks had loaned Kia 3.9 trillion
won.
</P>
<P>
The problem is to nomalize the supply of money in short-term
financial markets, said the bank officials.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that merchant banks are worried that customers
will rush to withdraw money from the short-term financial
institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
