<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ceasefire Reached for Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 19 (Xinhua) -- West African foreign ministers and
the military junta in Sierra Leone agreed on Friday an immediate
ceasefire in the troubled west African country.
</P>
<P>
After a two-day talks in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire, they also
agreed to meet again in a week's time to seek ways to return to
power the civilian government of Ahmed Tejan Kabbah overthrown in
a coup on May 25.
</P>
<P>
In a statement at the end of the talks, Nigerian Foreign
Minister Tom Ikimi announced that the two sides agreed "to
resolve all issues related to the Sierra Leone crisis
peacefully".
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held between a 14-man delegation of the junta
and the Committee of Four on Sierra Leone of the Economic
Ecommunity of West African States (ECOWAS), at the presence of
representatives from the Organization of African Unity (OAU) and
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The committee, made up of foreign ministers of Nigeria, Ghana,
Guinea and Cote d'Ivoire, was set up at the June 26 meeting of
ECOWAS foreign ministers in Conakry, Guinea, where a
three-pronged strategy was adopted towards resolving the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The strategy which included dialogue, sanctions and the use of
force, has been endorsed by the OAU and UN after approval by
ECOWAS leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Abidjan meeting is part of ECOWAS attempts at dialogue to
restore Kabbah's government.
</P>
<P>
According to sources close to the meeting, the dialogue
"achieved positive results under enormous pressure from outside,"
which raised hope of peace in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ikimi described the atmosphere of the meeting as
"cordial, friendly and brotherly," saying that exchanges enriched
the knowledge of both sides on the issues that generated the
coup.
</P>
<P>
Some soldiers launched a coup in Sierra Leone on May 25 and
ousted what they described as a corrupt government led by
President Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
The coup invited wide condemnation from the international
community, and west Africa in particular. ECOWAS peacekeeping
force, the Nigeria-led ECOMOG, has launched military intervention
in a bid to restore Kabbah's government, which put the west
African country in a very difficult situation.
</P>
<P>
The coup and the subsequent instability had increased the
suffering of the poorset people in Sierra Leone. Aid workers in
the country warned Friday that social and health conditions
deteriorated there, with more than 30,000 refugees having fled to
its neighbors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
