<HEADLINE> Thai Tourism Authority Sets Up Center to Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 19 (Xinhua) - The Tourism Authority of Thailand
(TAT) has set up a coordinating center to provide assistance to
foreign tourists affected by the Pattaya hotel fire last week.
</P>
<P>
The fire at the five-star Royal Jomtien resort hotel in Pattaya
left at least 90 people dead, mostly Thais.
</P>
<P>
The high death toll, mainly because of inadequate fire safety
measures, severely dented the country's image in the tourism
industry.
</P>
<P>
The center will work with other agencies to assist people who
are injured, have lost belongings, need new documents, or a place
to stay until they could return home, according to Juthamas
Siriwan, Deputy Governor of the TAT.
</P>
<P>
To restore foreign tourist confidence in the long run, the TAT
would coordinate a campaign to make accident-prevention measures
and inspection mandatory at hotels.
</P>
<P>
In future, in crisis related to the tourism industry, the TAT
will set up an information center to liaise with other
organizations, screen data and publicize facts to key news media
outlets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
