<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Police Seizes 78,000 Pirated CDs in Raid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Singapore police have seized
nearly 650,000 US dollars worth of pirated music compact discs
(CDs) and crippled an illegal syndicate which, as was believed,
commanded half the market in pirated CDs here, the Straits Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
It said that in its "most successful raid" on CD pirates to
date, the Criminal Investigation Department (CID) seized more than
78,000 CDs with a retail value of 940,000 Singapore dollars, or
about 650,000 US dollars, and arrested 13 people including the man
it believes to be the syndicate leader who was a former marketing
manager of a firm manufacturing CDs and CD-Roms.
</P>
<P>
In their operation, which started on Thursday and ended early
Friday, 50 officers from the CID's Commercial Crime and
Intelligence Divisions raided five places in the island country,
and captured, in addition to the pirated CDs, about 30,000
Singapore dollars (21,000 US dollars) worth of equipment used to
make "master" CDs which are duplicated at manufacturing plants,
and produce original cover designs of the CDs.
</P>
<P>
The Straits Times quoted CID director Chua Chin Kiat as saying
that the CID would concentrate its efforts on large syndicates,
because it would not be effective to hit small retailers like the
kind who run makeshift music stalls.
</P>
<P>
Music industry representatives estimate that for every three
music CDs sold in Singapore, one is likely to be a pirated CD.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, anyone found guilty of selling or distributing
articles which infringe copyrights can be fined up to 100,000
Singapore dollars and jailed for up to five years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
