<HEADLINE> India's Sea-Food Exports Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 19 (Xinhua) -- India's sea-food exports have
crossed the one billion US dollar mark for the third time in
succession, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The share of marine products in India's total export earnings
during the fiscal year 1996-97 (from April 1, 1996 to March 31,
1997) was 4.3 percent and exports have registered a 27.65 percent
growth in terms of volume and 17.72 percent by value.
</P>
<P>
Fin fish is the major item of export in terms of volume sharing
45.64 percent followed by frozen fin fish (27.88 percent), frozen
cuttlefish (18.40 percent).
</P>
<P>
Frozen shrimp continued to be the major items in the export in
terms of value, contributing 65.56 percent, followed by frozen
fish (15.36 percent).
</P>
<P>
The share of items such as cephalopods (squid, cuttlefish and
octopus), chilled items and lobsters has declined while that of
frozen fish, frozen shrimp, dried and live items increased their
share considerably, which resulted in the export growth.
</P>
<P>
Southeast Asia shared 52.19 percent of India's sea-food exports
in terms of volume and 21.33 percent in terms of value.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
