<HEADLINE> CPLP Decides to Strengthen Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the seven
CPLP countries today ended their first meeting in Brazil's eastern
city Salvador, during which they agreed to expand cooperation and
promote development of the community, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The Community of Portuguese-Speaking Countries (CPLP) was
formed in Lisbon, Portugal, last year with the aim of enhancing
the international role of the Portuguese language in an
increasingly English-speaking world.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of the seven member states, Brazil, Portugal,
Cape Verde, Guinea Bissau, Mozambique, Angola and Sao Tome and
Principe, attended the two-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
The leaders spoke highly of the progress the CPLP, especially
the five African members, achieved in cooperation on agricultural
development, food security, public health and fight against AIDS.
</P>
<P>
A series of plans on the community's future cooperation in the
fields of education, drug fighting, agricultural technology,
personnel training and management were also approved during the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The seven foreign ministers also reached an agreement that if
possible they would join efforts to help Brazil get a seat in an
expanded U.N. Security Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
