<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Holds DDC Elections Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Nepal holds elections today for
60 district development committees (DDC).
</P>
<P>
A total of 160,603 local representatives are expected to cast
ballots from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. to elect 60 DDC chairmen, 60 DDC
vice-chairmen and 766 DDC members, the Election Commission said.
</P>
<P>
The DDC elections, which have been put off twice, are the third
phase of the local elections in Nepal and are held on the basis of
proportional representation.
</P>
<P>
Elections for 3,192 village development committees (VDC) and 58
municipalities took place on May 17 and May 26 respectively, in
which the main ruling partner Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxist and Leninist, CPN-UML) won about 53 percent of the seats
contested.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML is expected to clinch a landslide victory again
this time.
</P>
<P>
It is already in a position to form at least 35 DDCs on its own
strength.
</P>
<P>
To ensure victory, it has allied with its ruling partner
National Democratic Party (RPP) in 16 districts, whereas the main
opposition Nepali Congress (NC) has also joined forces with the
RPP in more than 15 districts.
</P>
<P>
Before today's elections, 74 persons have already been elected
unopposed, including one DDC vice-chairman and 73 DDC members.
</P>
<P>
Among them, 53 are from the CPN-UML and eight each from the RPP
and NC.
</P>
<P>
Teams of polling officers and security personnel have been
dispatched to the polling centers to see that violence rampant in
the May local polls do not happen again.  
</P>
</TEXT>
