<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockheed Martin Tops List in 1996 Defense Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. companies, led by
Mariland-based Lockheed Martin Corp., represent six of the top 10
companies in worldwide defense sales in 1996, according to a
Defense News survey released today.
</P>
<P>
The leading international newsweekly said in its seventh annual
survey of the top 100 worldwide defense firms that Lockheed Martin
Corp. continued to rank first in the top 100, reporting 14.3
billion U.S. dollars in defense sales.
</P>
<P>
Lockheed's nearest rival, U.S.-based military aircraft and
missile manufacturer McDonnell Douglas Corp., reported 10.1
billion U.S. dollars defense sales.
</P>
<P>
British Aerospace, plc, maintained its 1995 third-place
ranking, with defense revenue rising from 6.5 billion dollars in
1995 to 9.0 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Northrop Grumman, which ranked fifth worldwide in 1995, ranked
fourth in 1996, with 6.7 billion dollars; and Hughes Electronics
Corp. ranked fifth this year, with 6.3 billion dollars defense
sales.
</P>
<P>
Lockheed Martin's impending merger with Northrop Grumman will
create a giant 21.5 billion dollar defense company while the
Boeing-McDonnell Douglas merger will create a 16 billion dollar
defense firm, the Defense News said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that European companies are rebounding from a
difficult period of unprofitability, but the growth of megadefense
companies in the United States poses unprecedented challenges to
their long-term viability.
</P>
<P>
The 10 largest European companies increased combined annual
defense sales from 30.1 billion dollars to 37.8 billion dollars.
Profits of the 10 firms totaled 4.12 billion dollars in 1996, up
from a loss of 1.13 billion dollars the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The top 10 U.S. companies' combined annual sales fell slightly
from 59.6 billion dollars to 59.4 billion dollars. However, the 10
largest U.S. defense companies in the 1997 survey had combined net
income of 6.4 billion dollars, the Defense News said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
