<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine May Delay Chernobyl Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine may revise its 1995
memorandum with the G7 countries on closure of the Chernobyl
nuclear plant since the G7 has failed to finance the shutdown,
Environment Minister Yury Kostenko said recently.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Kostenko criticized a decision made by
G7 leaders at Denver summit last month to provide 300 million
U.S. dollars for constructing a new sarcophagus over the cripple
fourth Chernobyl reactor and to call an international conference
this October to raise additional funds for the project.
</P>
<P>
"By calling this conference, the G7 wants to get the remainder
of the required funds from other donor countries," said
Kostenko. "But I doubt that these countries are capable of giving
more than the G7."
</P>
<P>
Kostenko put the total cost of constructing the new sarcophagus
at 750 million dollars. He added that G7 had initially accepted
this figure but later dismissed it.
</P>
<P>
Kostenko's comments echoed Foreign Minister Gennady Udovenko's
criticism of the G7 at the U.N. Earth Summit in New York. On June
26, Udovenko said the world's industrial giants have been slow in
providing technical advice and financial aid for the Chernobyl
closure.
</P>
<P>
Kostenko said Ukraine would decide what parts of the 1995
memorandum need revision after it becomes clear how much money the
G7 would disburse for construction of the new sarcophagus and
completion of two new nuclear reactors meant to offset the closure
of Chernobyl.
</P>
<P>
Under the memorandum, completion of two partially built
reactors, one at the Khmelnytsky power station and the other at
the Rivne power station, is to be funded by the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development (EBRD), which has however been
reluctant to commit itself to providing the required 1.2 billion
dollars, saying that the project was not economically efficient.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine has consistently vowed to finish the two reactors with
or without EBRD financing. Kostenko said the EBRD was to make a
final decision on funding for the project by mid-July.
</P>
<P>
Indicating that the current financial uncertainties could lead
Ukraine to give up the sarcophagus project altogether, Kostenko
said the government is considering plans to upgrade the existing
sarcophagus, which was hastily built in the wake of the 1986
catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
The plans involve the extraction of nuclear fuel from inside
the crippled reactor, "Leaving the fuel under the sarcophagus is
even more dangerous than a decision not to close the whole plant,"
said Kostenko.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed the government's earlier plans to restart the
first Chernobyl reactor, which was shut down last November. "Work
is in progress for bringing the reactor back on line, although the
budgetary funds allocated for this purpose are not sufficient," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 state budget approved by the parliament allocates 20
million hryvnas (about 11 million dollars) for maintenance work at
Chernobyl. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970719.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Currency Further Weakens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Thai currency baht further
weakened on Friday on strong demand for dollars ahead of a long
weekend, depreciating about 18 percent compared with its value
before its float on July 2.
</P>
<P>
On Friday the baht was quoted at 30.40-30.50 against the dollar
in the onshore market, falling 20-30 Satang from the morning.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand announced its reference rate for
Thursday's trading at 30.127 baht to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The reference rate represents an average of rates traded over
the previous day.
</P>
<P>
On June 30, the last trading day before the baht's float, the
central bank's official midrate was 25.75 baht to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
With Saturday and Sunday being religious holidays, Monday and
Tuesday are made public holidays to compensate.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the central bank on Friday raised the ceiling on
term deposit interest rates offered by local financial
institutions. The commercial bank limit was raised from 12 percent
to 14 percent, and from 14 percent to 17 percent for finance
firms.
</P>
<P>
Overnight interbank rates closed at 14-15 percent, as liquidity
pressures eased slightly in the money market, with support by the
central bank.
</P>
<P>
Liquidity over the past several weeks has been extremely tight,
with interbank rates quoted as high as 20-25 percent, as capital
outflow continues amid concerns about the health of local
financial institutions and the shift in deposits between finance
companies and local banks.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Japanese Finance Minister Hiroshima
Mitsuzuka told his visiting Thai counterpart Thanong Bidaya that
the Japanese government would work together with the Thai
government in stemming the fall of the baht, including purchases
of the Thai currency.
</P>
<P>
In April last year, the two countries signed a securities
repurchase agreement, under which central banks needing US dollars
will be able to borrow foreign reserves from each other against
collateral in the form of US treasuries. They can then use the
dollars to help stabilize their currency markets.
</P>
<P>
A stabilized baht would also benefit Japan, which is Thailand's
biggest foreign investor.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
