<DOCNO> XIE19970719.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Clamps Down on Illegal Cigarette Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- China, the world's largest tobacco
consumer, will deal cigarette smuggling and forgery a heavy blow
through enacting a new tobacco monopoly law.
</P>
<P>
The Tobacco Monopoly Law Implementing Rules of the People's
Republic of China, following a tobacco monopoly law passed in
1993, has been issued early this month.
</P>
<P>
"The move indicates that the state is determined to discourage
the growth of the tobacco industry through firm regulations and
taxation," today's China Daily quoted Ni Yijin, president of the
State Tobacco Monopoly Administration, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The new law demands China's customs, public security agencies
and frontier guards to jointly crack down on cigarette
smuggling. Local tobacco monopoly bureaux must work with the
technological supervision administrations and industry and
commerce administrations to take rigorous measures to stamp out
fake brands.
</P>
<P>
Producers without license will be forced to close their
factories and face heavy fines while their products will be
confiscated and burned, according to the law.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, illegal production and sale of cigarette
paper, filter and manufacturing machines must be stopped and heavy
fines imposed.
</P>
<P>
Each year, nearly 50 billion cigarettes are smuggled into
the country, and 50 billion shoddy and fake cigarettes find their
way into the vast market, while another 50 billion cigarettes were
produced by illegal underground factories, the paper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970719.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
