<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank Offers Low-interest Loans to Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's central bank has
established a 20-billion-baht (667 million US dollar) low-interest
fund which could be made available to key enterprises hit by the
baht's float since July 2.
</P>
<P>
So far 13 enterprises have applied for loans from the fund,
which carries an 8 percent interest rate, to cushion the impact of
the baht depreciation.
</P>
<P>
The baht was quoted at 30.40-30.50 against the US dollar on
Friday in the onshore market, having depreciated about 18 percent
since July 2.
</P>
<P>
At present only businesses suffering as a direct result of the
baht float can apply for loans from the fund, according to
Chatumongol Sonakul, permanent secretary of the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
But he said the guidelines might be relaxed to allow
enterprises which have since run into trouble to borrow from the
fund, provided they are considered important to the economy.
</P>
<P>
A panel, headed by Chatumongol, has been set up to consider
which firms are qualified to the cheaper loan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, real estate developers in 14 southern provinces want
financial support from the government to help restore their
battered businesses.
</P>
<P>
They also request the Finance Ministry to arrange for financial
institutions to extend low-cost funding to smaller developers.
</P>
</TEXT>
