<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relief Urged for Flood Hit Eastern and Central Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The International Federation of Red
Cross and Red Crescent today called on the international community
to provide disaster relief to Poland, the Czech Republic, Slovakia
and Hungary, which have been hit by catastrophic floods.
</P>
<P>
A report of the federation said that nearly seven million Swiss
francs (about 5.52 million U.S. dollars) of relief aid are needed
for the four east and central European countries, where a worst
flood in centuries has caused great losses in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 100 people have been killed in the Czech
Republic and Poland and a total of more than 2.5 million people in
the four countries have been affected by the floods.
</P>
<P>
The supply of water, power and gas has been cut down in many
disaster areas and tens of thousands of people have been evacuated
out of the areas.
</P>
<P>
The federation has earlier offered five million Swiss francs
(about four million dollars) of emergency aid to the four
countries.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the federation said that the weather forecast
shows the situation will be worsened by the predicted heavier rain
fall in the coming days and they asked the international community
to provide emergency relief materials to the area as soon as
possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
