<HEADLINE> Beijing Cuts Administrative Fees to Attract Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital plans to
absorb more foreign investment into infrastructure, housing
construction and advanced science and technology projects by
cutting administrative fees formerly collected from investors.
</P>
<P>
"Methods, including preferential policies, will be discussed
this year to encourage foreign investment in these sectors," Yuan
Zhenyu, director of the Beijing Planning Commission, was quoted by
today's "China Daily" as saying.
</P>
<P>
The State Planning Commission and the Ministry of Finance have
cancelled 48 items of fees formerly collected in the course of
construction. They include some procedural and managerial fees
which have contributed to the high cost of building.
</P>
<P>
These fees account for 20-30 percent of housing costs in some
major cities, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Investment from foreign countries, Hong Kong and Macao has been
gradually diverted to Beijing's housing and infrastructure,
tourism and entertainment facilities, Yuan said.
</P>
<P>
Construction at several housing projects, financed by firms
from Hong Kong, Taiwan and Macao, was scheduled to start this year.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has attracted investment from 138 of the world's 500
biggest multi-national corporations, and 80 multi-nationals have
established their investment branches in the city.  
</P>
</TEXT>
