<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Concerned Over U.S. Nuclear Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
criticized and expressed concern about the subcritical nuclear
weapon test conducted by the United States on July 2.
</P>
<P>
"Although the test is not covered by the comprehensive test ban
treaty (CTBT) signed only last year, basically it contravenes the
treaty's spirit and conscience"', the Foreign Ministry here said
Friday in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Such an test is not conducive to the process of disarmament,
especially of nuclear arms, for which all nations have been
waiting for so long, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Although subcritical experiments are aimed at ensuring the
safety of nuclear arms, such tests could be used to improve
unclear arms.
</P>
<P>
With the test, other countries in possession of nuclear weapons
were being encouraged to do likewise -- a development that reduced
the CTBT's significance, it said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia therefore calls on the U.S. government to review its
decision to carry out a series of subcritical tests, and urged
other nations to refrain from such testing.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia believes non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and
nuclear disarmament can be attained only if all countries in the
world, those possessing nuclear weapons in particular, are
strongly committed to the objectives, the statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970719.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou New Airport Ready for Takeoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Construction of the Guangzhou New
International Airport has been given final clearance, as the project
received central government approval yesterday and construction
will begin within the year.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily quoted Guangzhou mayor Li Shusen as saying
that a shareholding system will be introduced to raise necessary
funds.
</P>
<P>
The gigantic project in Guangzhou's Baiyun District and the
suburban city Huadu, will cost about 20 billion yuan (2.4 billion
US dollars). Both an expressway and elevated railway will be built
to link the airport to the downtown.
</P>
<P>
Located 28 km away from the city proper and covering 1,600
hectares, the new airport will be 1,270 hectares larger than the
present Guangzhou Baiyun Airport.
</P>
<P>
The new airport will be able to accommodate 80 million
passengers and 2.5 million tons of cargo annually. It will have
three runways -- one 4,000 m long and the other two 3,700 m each.
</P>
<P>
The floor space will be 280,000 sq. m, ample space for the
terminal to accommodate 10,000 passengers during peak hours.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion of first phase -- including construction of two
runways in 2005 -- the new airport will be able to handle 27
million passengers and 740,000 tons of cargo.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou has become one of busiest air traffic hubs in China,
and the Guangzhou Baiyun coped with 12.644 million passengers last
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
