<HEADLINE> Tourism Zone in South China Invites Global Bids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- International bids were invited
yesterday for the 300-million-US-dollar, first-phase construction
of a massive development zone near Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Chuandao Island Tourism Experimental Zone, located west of
Macao and Hong Kong, covers 21.3 sq. km of Xiachuan Island's
mountainous area and 80 sq. km of nearby coast, according to
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodia China Town Group decided to invest 300 million US
dollars over the next five years in infrastructure, the paper
quoted group chairman Luo Dazhan as saying. Luo also chairs a
joint venture with the local government which functions as the
developer of the zone.
</P>
<P>
The zone will eventually become another major seaport for south
and southwest China, as businesses, including aquaculture,
agriculture, fodder production, tourism, processing and high-tech
development, will be established.
</P>
<P>
The zone's first phase, to be completed within five years,
includes a 650 million yuan (78.4 million US dollars),
6.4-kilometer bridge linking the island with the mainland, the 500
million yuan (60.3 million US dollars) Wangfu port, a 200 million
yuan (24.1 million US dollars) 10-km portion of a 70-km highway
and a 500 million yuan (60.3 million US dollars) project to
convert 70 sq. km of sea into land.
</P>
<P>
Interested parties will have to submit their bids before
September 28, said Luo.  
</P>
