<HEADLINE> Tajik Government, Opposition Exchange POWs Near Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Tajik government and the
opposition today exchanged seven prisoners of war (POW) near the
capital Dushambe, the Interfax new agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The report said the exchange, supervised by international
observers, took place at a village some 250 kilometers from the
capital.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed in Moscow on June 27, POWs should be
exchanged on the basis of equal numbers. The second group of POWs
were supposed to be exchanged Saturday.
</P>
<P>
At present, the opposition still holds 249 government soldiers.
</P>
<P>
At today's ceremony, both parties promised to keep their word
and push forward the peace process in the country.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after its independence in 1991, the central Asian
nation began to suffer internal strife. Opposition forces, exiled
to and based in Afghanistan, exchanged fire with the Tajik
government troops near the border and launched terrorist bombings
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The peace process started in 1994 on the initiative of the
United Nations, leading to the signing of a general agreement on
peace and national concord in June this year. 
</P>
