<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Cancels 700 Mining Concessions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica's Mines and Energy
Ministry today announced the cancellation of some 700 mining
concessions granted for their exploitation.
</P>
<P>
"We used to grant concessions to anybody, but now we want these
activities to be responsible and friendly to the environment," the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
A controversy arose here when it was announced that some
Canadian companies would start to exploit gold deposits in strip
mines in the northern zone and the central Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Despite assurances from the ministry that precautions had been
adopted to protect the environment, strong current of public
opinion were generated against this kind of exploitation.
</P>
<P>
Those who are against it said the strip mining would cause
negative effects on environment since it requires big amounts of
water which will contaminate adjoining terrain, rivers and seas
if not properly treated before disposition.
</P>
<P>
They also argued that this kind of mining would bring about
serious social problems, hamper the development of agriculture and
leave at the end of the exploitation a barren environment.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica has an estimated 6 million ounces of gold in
reserve, with a market value of 2.2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 28 franchises engaged in gold
exploitation in the country, mainly in the southern and the
northern central zone and the central Pacific areas.
</P>
<P>
The concessions cover an area of 127 square kilometers,
representing nearly 1 percent of the national territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
