<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic briefs from Latin American countries this week:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The Argentine Economy Ministry confirmed that
the country produced 52 million tons of foodgrains during the
1996-1997 harvest, the biggest in its history.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that the figures could increase slightly
after corn, sorgum and beans are all reaped.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico is expected to harvest 800,000 tons of
avocado this year and the producers will have to expand the
markets to Europe and East Asia, said the Association of Avocado
Producers.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguayan imports in the 12 months upto in April
reached 3.5 billion U.S. dollars, a 19.7 percent increase over the
same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian copper imports during the first two
months of this year increased 84.2 percent over the same period of
1996. The demand through June reached 137,000 tons, of which
75,000, or 54.7 percent, were met through imports.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's total copper demand this year was estimated at 282,000
tons, of which 160,000 or 56.7 percent needs to be imported.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- the Escondida deposit in Chile produced 480,348
tons of fine copper during the first half of this year,
registering a 17.5 percent increase compared to the same period in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The La Minera fine copper produced 74,007 tons in June.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Some 800 million U.S. dollars will be invested
in the next five years in projects approved by the Interoceanic
Region Authority (ARI), said its director, Nicolas Ardito Barletta.
</P>
<P>
Among the projects awaiting ARI approval are processing zones
for exports and touristic development in Gamboa and Amador.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The Costa Rican currency, colon, devaluated
in the first six months of this year 5.7 percent against the
U.S. dollar, as shown by the Central Bank statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
