<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Nino Affects Fishing in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Colombian authorities
urged fishermen to take measures to avoid a decline in their catch
resulting from the climate phenomenon "El Nino."
</P>
<P>
The weather changes in the southeastern Pacific Ocean have
reduced the population of tuna, mackerel, herring and other
species in the zone, said the National Institute of Fishing and
Aquaculture (INPA) in a communique published today.
</P>
<P>
Two ground seas occurred recently in the Pacific coast of
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
El Nino, which causes rainstorms, is a warming-up current in
the Pacific Ocean near the Equator.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the temperature rise in sea near the coast has
led some marine species to migrate to colder high seas out of
fishermen's reach. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970719.0200 </DOCNO>
